    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="4" id="s4" slide="4" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="" course="">
        <keyword chapter="" slide="4">Trichromatic Color Theory</keyword>
      </keywords>
      <h3 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Trichromatic Color Theory</paragraphs>
      </h3>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> The </paragraphs>
      <b xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Trichromatic Color Theory</paragraphs>
      </b>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> orginates from the work of Thomas Young and Hermann von Helmholtz in the 19th century.
They postulated that the human eye senses light via three types of photoreceptors,
each sensitive to a light of wavelengths within a particular range.</paragraphs>
      <newline course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""></p>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/YoungHelm.jpg" environment="" />
      </div>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="5" id="s5" slide="5" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="" course="">
        <keyword chapter="" slide="5">Cone Cells</keyword>
      </keywords>
      <h3 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Cone Cells</paragraphs>
      </h3>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> In a currently prevalent scientific model,
color perception is effected by the stimulation of photoreceptor cells on the retina.
One class of such cells are called </paragraphs>
      <b xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">cone cells</paragraphs>
      </b>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">,
of which there are three types: </paragraphs>
      <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">L</paragraphs>
      </strong>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">, </paragraphs>
      <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">M</paragraphs>
      </strong>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">,  and </paragraphs>
      <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">S</paragraphs>
      </strong>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">.
Their responsiveness to light of various ranges of wavelengths
peak at approximately: </paragraphs>
      <ul xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> 564 - 580 nm (</paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">L</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">ong wavelength), </paragraphs>
        </li>
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> 534 - 545 nm (</paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">M</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">edium), </paragraphs>
        </li>
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> 420 - 440 nm (</paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">S</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">hort), </paragraphs>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> respectively. </paragraphs>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""></p>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1e/Cones_SMJ2_E.svg" environment="" />
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Normalized responsivity spectra of human cone cells, S, M, and L types
(from </paragraphs>
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_cell" environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Wikipedia</paragraphs>
        </a>
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">.) </paragraphs>
      </div>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="">
        <img src="https://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach-dev/images/Linear_visible_spectrum.svg" environment="" />
      </div>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="6" id="s6" slide="6" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="6" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> In the </paragraphs>
      <b xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Opponent Process Model</paragraphs>
      </b>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">,
signals from the cone cells (and rod cells) go through another layer of processing,
in which calculations based on the relative strengths of the signals
give rise to our perception of hue, saturation/chroma and brightness/lightness.</paragraphs>
      <newline course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="7" id="s7" slide="7" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="7" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> In one proposed model, the opponent process filters signals from photoreceptor cells into
three channels of </paragraphs>
      <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">opponent</paragraphs>
      </i>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> color sensations: </paragraphs>
      <ul xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Red-Green (</paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">R-G</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">) </paragraphs>
        </li>
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Yellow-Blue (</paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Y-B</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">) </paragraphs>
        </li>
        <li environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Black-White (the </paragraphs>
          <strong environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">A</paragraphs>
          </strong>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">chromatic response channel) </paragraphs>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""></p>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" style="width:100%" environment="">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8d/Diagram_of_the_opponent_process.png" environment="" />
      </div>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="8" id="s8" slide="8" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="8" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Experimental data suggest that our perception of red and green is derived from the </paragraphs>
      <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">difference</paragraphs>
      </i>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> between the stimuli from the L and M cone cells,
in a manner which is </paragraphs>
      <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">antagonistic</paragraphs>
      </i>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">. </paragraphs>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""></p>
      <newcol course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
        <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> This means that, perceptually, one color being </paragraphs>
        <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs">more</paragraphs>
        </i>
        <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> red than another
is equivalent to it being </paragraphs>
        <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs">less</paragraphs>
        </i>
        <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> green, and vice versa. </paragraphs>
        <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"></p>
        <collapse course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
          <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Along the same vein,  we cannot </paragraphs>
          <i xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs">psychologically</paragraphs>
          </i>
          <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> conceive of a color which is both
reddish and greenish. </paragraphs>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"></p>
          <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Note that, seemingly paradoxically, red and green mix additively to produce yellow,
but most of us do not perceive yellow as being both reddish and greenish. </paragraphs>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"></p>
          <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> On the other hand, we have no problem seeing the color cyan as being both green and blue. </paragraphs>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"></p>
          <collapse course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
            <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Similarly, the color sensation of yellow-versus-blue is also processed antagonistically.
No color is perceived as being yellowish and bluish at the same time. </paragraphs>
            <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"></p>
            <collapse course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
              <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Moreover, the red-green and yellow-blue channels are independent from each other.
Hence, red and green are both perceived as neither yellow or blue, and
yellow and blue are perceived as neither red or green. </paragraphs>
            </collapse>
          </collapse>
        </collapse>
      </newcol>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="9" id="s9" slide="9" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="9" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="">
        <img style="width:360px" src="https://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach-dev/images/hurvich_jameson_diag.jpg" environment="" />
        <div style="text-align:center" environment="">
          <br environment="" />
          <i environment="">
            <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">An Opponent-Process Theory of Color Vision</paragraphs>
          </i>
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">, L. Hurvich, D. Jameson </paragraphs>
        </div>
      </div>
      <center xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">   </paragraphs>
        <iframe scrolling="no" style="height:720px;width:100%;text-align:center" src="https://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach-dev/content/uged1533/color/add_mix1.html" environment=""></iframe>
      </center>
      <comment course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="">@slide
It has been proposed that an S cone stimulus contributes positively to the
red-green channel.
Under this proposition, it is easy to see why spectral colors towards the violet
end of the visible color spectrum appears reddish.
&lt;p/&gt;
Moreover, this explains why, perceptually,
it appears natural to wrap the visible hue spectrum
into a color wheel, with magenta serving as the link between violet and red.
&lt;p/&gt;&lt;div class='image'&gt;&lt;img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/38/BYR_color_wheel.svg"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p/&gt;&lt;div class='image'&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach-dev/images/Linear_visible_spectrum.svg"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p/&gt;
(Food for thought: there is no magenta on the rainbow.)
</comment>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="10" id="s10" slide="10" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="10" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> In an opponent process model, our perception of color is established via comparison.
This may explain some of the color illusions which result when we place colors of
different hues or lightness adjacent to each other,
e.g. a neutral grey appearing pinkish next to a greenish blue color. </paragraphs>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""></p>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="dual" environment="">
        <div class="dual-left" environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> &lt;svg width="300px" height="300px"&gt;
&lt;rect x="0" y="0" width="300" height="300" fill="#0ee" /&gt;
&lt;rect x="100" y="100" width="100" height="100" fill="#ddd" /&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt; </paragraphs>
        </div>
        <div class="dual-right" environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> &lt;svg width="300px" height="300px"&gt;
&lt;rect x="100" y="100" width="100" height="100" fill="#ddd" /&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt; </paragraphs>
        </div>
      </div>
    </slide>
    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="11" id="s11" slide="11" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="11" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> It also explains the illusion of complementary </paragraphs>
      <b xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">afterimages</paragraphs>
      </b>
      <paragraphs course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">, where, for example,
someone having stared at a red color for a long time who then suddenly looks upon
a white sheet might see a green color. </paragraphs>
    </slide>
