    <slide environment="" chapter_type="" wbtag="slide" canon_num="14" id="s14" slide="14" course="" chapter="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="">
      <keywords slide="14" environ="slide" chapter="" course=""/>
      <blockquote xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> If you mean to represent great darkness, it
must be done by contrasting it with great light;
on the contrary, if you want to produce great
brightness, you must oppose to it a very dark
shade : so a pale yellow will cause red to appear
more beautiful than if opposed to a purple colour.</paragraphs>
        <newline xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">There is another rule, by observing which,
though you do not increase the natural beauty of
the colours, yet by bringing them together they
may give additional grace to each other, as green
placed near red, while the effect would be quite
the reverse, if placed near blue. </paragraphs>
      </blockquote>
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="text-align:right" environment="">
        <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Leonardo da Vinci, </paragraphs>
        <i environment="">
          <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="" chapter="" chapter_type="" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Treatise on Painting</paragraphs>
        </i>
      </div>
      <hr xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="" />
      <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="dual" environment="">
        <div class="dual-left" environment="">
          <a title="Joaquín Sorolla&#10;, Public domain, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Joaqu%C3%ADn_Sorolla_-_Barcas_en_la_Playa,_Valencia_(1894).jpg" environment="">
